http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rvppl</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2013</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>14EF1EB9-67DC-4153-959B-1ED7BB553E2C</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Societal</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Dissolved silica (DSi) concentrations have been measured for Lake Baikal and it's main catchment rivers. We have found that DSi concentrations are highest in the Selenga River than elsewhere. 

Stable isotope analyses of DSi (30Si) from rivers show that values are higher than surrounding rocks, which is to be expected due to weathering and biological activity. Highest isotope values are to be found in the lake, linked to more intense biological update by diatoms and other algae.

In Lake Baikal itself, highest 30Si values occur when productivity is highest, between 10-40 m in upper waters. Isotope values reveal that there is no dissolution of diatoms down through the water column. 

Isotopic values (30Si) of diatom silica itself in the upper lake sediments are overall lower than surrounding DSi because of biological fractionation. However, there is considerable late Holocene variability which we are still interpreting. 

2016: we have recently published findings that demonstrate that the isotopic signature of 30Si was transferred from contemporary Lake Baikal to the sediment record with no impact from secondary processes such as dissolution. This strengthens our confidence of interpretations of palaeo-isotope data.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>These data will be of interest to other academics studying global carbon and silicon cycles, and researchers applying 30Si technique to freshwaters.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>9229DC7F-5717-4C19-AC55-6205EDFD2998</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.biogeosciences.net/13/147/2016/</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/C81D47C1-0485-4867-BA1B-D7FAC3909425"><gtr:id>C81D47C1-0485-4867-BA1B-D7FAC3909425</gtr:id><gtr:title>Holocene carbon dynamics at the forest-steppe ecotone of southern Siberia.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Global change biology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/e42d6941c67ce1ac87b5846afd9f3db2"><gtr:id>e42d6941c67ce1ac87b5846afd9f3db2</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Mackay AW</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2017-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1354-1013</gtr:issn></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/03203337-C96B-4D2A-B1BC-535FB82F7181"><gtr:id>03203337-C96B-4D2A-B1BC-535FB82F7181</gtr:id><gtr:title>Ecology under lake ice.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Ecology letters</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/dd1333a6719aa8d81ae39b9d981dc634"><gtr:id>dd1333a6719aa8d81ae39b9d9